			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: confused...<a name="52370"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 17 04 5:35 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>The main reason for having taunt is for when you are a low level bard trying to fill in the tank role. At low levels the differences between classes are much less pronounced and I personally found I was fairly often asked to do this.
<br />

<br />
However, when I was a young bard our songs generated huge amounts of aggro. Just a couple of rounds of hymn juggling in a lute early in a fight were often enough to put me at the top of the hate list. This is simply not an option for bards in the game as it stands now.
<br />

<br />
So in fact I was one of those calling for a taunt song, but only in conjunction with the point about improving jig. Basically I would like to see jig replaced with a song that actually benefits low level bards, and the lack of any means to taunt is the biggest issue I can see facing them right now.
<br />

<br />
Unfortunately some of the points made in the discussion threads have been split up rather more than I might have personally liked in the ensuing polls, whilst a few others have been excluded completely. But then a system like this is never going to work perfectly.
<br />

<br />
But yes, coming from the point of view of a high level bard you are correct. From around level 40 we have the means to hold some aggro when combined with firm aggro control by the other members of the group. But below this there is a definite gap in a bard's ability to generate aggro compared to the original class design. It is in that gap where a taunt song might be useful.
<br />

<br />
