			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: confused...<a name="52796"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 20 04 10:58 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I'm really glad someone brought this up.
<br />

<br />
If a bard (post level 30) is doing content at the level and in the gear it was anticipated, you have absolutely no need for a taunt button.  If you're bazaar twinked to the max, though, maybe up to about level 60 you could tank some stuff if you could hold aggro.
<br />

<br />
I'm very worried that as a community we've identified TAUNT as one of our two primary concerns.  As a class, we have no business taunting; we were designed to NOT be able to do some things: quick heal and tank spring to mind.  By asking for one of those abilities, we're all but telling the devs that we're happy with our ability to do what we WERE designed to do - be a force multiplier and ultra-flexible support class.
<br />

<br />
I'm totally opposed to bard taunt.  It's not something we should have (from a class balance perspective); it's not something we should ask for (since we can only ask for a certain number of things and we have other very pressing problems); and when you get to a certain level of content, it's just not something you even want.
<br />

<br />
I hope all of you that play your bards as primary characters and who play your bard socially (be it casually in groups or hard core as raiders) participate in the class balance discussion at eqlive in the class balance forum.  Right now, I think the chorus of very ignorant fair-weather bard players (who couldn't be bothered to participate at EQDiva or tCH) are going to decide our future by dominating the class balance discussion on bards.  What they ask for and what we get may truly destroy our class if we let it happen.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
